Deadpool Vs Spiderman

A simple image classifier, built using Fastai Library. We will use a pre-trained

Mar 12, 2020 â€¢ 6 min read

Here we are going to use the Fastai deep learning library, which is built upon PyTorch, to build an image classifier to determine if the image supplied is that of Deadpool or Spiderman. We'll use a pre-trained model, the Resnet34 model. We are going to train it further on a set of Deadpool and Spiderman images, downloaded from the internet.

%reload_ext autoreload
%autoreload 2
%matplotlib inline

Next we perform all the necessary imports

from pathlib import Path
import os
import PIL.Image
from fastai.vision import *
from fastai.metrics import error_rate

Removing corrupt images

Set up the paths where we have downloaded the images, I have used the 'google-images-download' utitlity, which can be easily installed using pip, to download the images that'll be used in the training / validation sets.

path =  Path('/home/ubuntu/data/train')

spidey_path = path/'spiderman'
deadpool_path = path/'deadpool'

Next, we check for and remove corrupt images in our set of downloads.

def find_broken_img(path):
    broken_images = []
    valid_count = 0
    err_count = 0
    for pic in os.listdir(path):
        try:
            im = PIL.Image.open(f'{path}/{pic}')
            im.verify()
            valid_count += 1
        except (IOError, SyntaxError) as e:
            err_count += 1
            broken_images.append(Path(f'{path}/{pic}'))
    
    return valid_count, err_count, broken_images

valid_count, err_count, broken_images = find_broken_img(spidey_path)
print("Valid Spidey Images : {}".format(valid_count))
print("Erroneous Images : {}".format(err_count))
print('Removing broken spidey files...')

for path in broken_images:
    os.remove(path)
    

Valid Spidey Images : 130
Erroneous Images : 0

valid_count, err_count, broken_images = find_broken_img(deadpool_path)
print("Valid Deadpool Images : {}".format(valid_count))
print("Erroneous Images : {}".format(err_count))
print('Removing broken deadpool files...')

for path in broken_images:
    os.remove(path)

printing first sample /home/ubuntu/data/train/deadpool/__59a48ed7599d0.jpg

We load our images inside the fastai ImageDataBunch object, which will be passed on to our model for training and validation.

Note : The parameter 'ds_tfms' is a little tricky, one of the transformations takes padding_mode='reflection' by default, which will throw errors down the line. Refer to this thread for more information : https://forums.fast.ai/t/unable-to-change-padding-to-zeros-when-using-rotation-warp-from-get-transforms/27847/4

tfms = get_transforms()
data = ImageDataBunch.from_folder('/home/ubuntu/data/', valid_pct=0.2, ds_tfms = tfms, size=224, padding_mode='zeros')

data.show_batch(rows=3, figsize=(8,10))

The Data Bunch object also contains the classes

print(data.classes)

['deadpool', 'spiderman']

learner = create_cnn(data, models.resnet34, metrics=error_rate)
